GOVERNMENT ANNOUNCES PLANS FOR INTELLECTUALIZATION
OF INFORMATION HIGHWAY THROUGH MENTUFACTURING

In an unexpected White House press conference on 
April 1, Vice-President Albert Gore announced 
Microsoft's Bill Gates would be named director 
of a new agency designed to regulate and stimulate 
the development of the Information Superhighway.

"If you have a personal computer, chances are 
that Mr. Gates and Microsoft Corp. are already a 
part of your life," said Gore during the conference. 
"In many cases, the personal computer is the on-ramp to
the information highway, the conduit through which 
much of the national intellectual product of the 
future will flow.  This intellectual product, or property,
is manufactured, but not - in the conventional sense -
through machinery.  Rather, the commerce of the
information highway is the harvest of the mind,
our mental facilities. 'Mentufacturing' is the word 
the PR backroom guys -<laughter>- have coined.  
Mr. Gates's excellence in the field make him the 
logical candidate for a new project to guide and
accelerate the nation's transition to a mentufacturing 
industrial base."

Gore went on to explain how Gates, along with a 
core consulting group consisting of 
telecommunications guru John Malone and cellular 
phone titan Craig McCaw, would make up the 
industry-government interface for the agency, 
tentatively named the Ministry of Mentufacturing, 
Organization, Networking and Electronic Exchange 
(MO*MONEE). 

The ministry is to be located at 2001 L
Street NW, Washington, D.C., alongside offices 
of the Business Software Alliance.

The initial mandate of the ministry, said Gore,
would be to work up a plan for the issuing of
Licenses of Mentufactury, which would become  
necessary - just as the motor vehicle operator's
license is a must for drivers - for the operation 
of on-line services or the production of 
intellectual "soft goods."  Gore said that he, along 
with Congress, would move briskly toward legislation 
requiring Licenses of Mentufactury for all computer
industry and information highway entrepeneurs
by late 1995.

Roger Thrush, an administrative lieutenant speaking
for the absent Gates, who was vacationing in Hawaii,
explained how licensing would work.

"It really is simpler than it sounds," said Thrush.
"We envision several classes of mentufacturing, the
primary of which constitutes existing on-line services
and retail software developers in the Fortune 500. For 
the most part, this group has already been granted 
provisionary licenses with permanent approval contingent 
only upon minor structural and operational changes 
which we think will be no inconvenience to implement.
For example, most of the captains of the information
industry already have the capability to suborn their 
telecommunications feeds to something we call the 
Microserve and Mentufacturing Market Organizational
Network - or MAMMON - backbone, a super-net which will 
make the registration of Licenses of Mentufactury 
electronic, instantaneous and economical.

"For the small businessman - or millions of home hobbyists -
there will be a different class of license.  This should
make it easier for the government to distinguish legitimate 
mentufacturing needs from socially heretical activity.  For 
example, we would consider the bulletin board system 
application for a Licence of Mentufactury from a member 
of the North American Man-Boy Love Association frivolous.  
And this has an added benefit, because it allows for 
interactive, non-intrusive patrol of the information highway, 
thus hindering those who would use it for soliciting, 
piracy, or the dissemination of private, sensitive or 
proprietary information.  Of course, the small 
businessman with a 5-6 line service will find 
the legislation transparent, which should make the 
cyber civil libertarians happy," Thrush laughed.

Licenses of Mentufactury will be assigned tariffs based on 
a sliding scale beginning at $500, said Thrush.  
Fees would go to a government superfund, controlled 
by MO*MONEE. The superfund would be used for federal 
employee reimbursement and seed cash for promising 
breakthroughs in mentufacturing.

Silicon Valley venture capitalist and ex-Gates paramour
Ann Winblad said in interview, "Bill has wanted to 
adopt the mindset of a true visionary, to take even 
greater risks, for a long time. No one can doubt the 
scope of his ambition and his great admiration for 
Henry Ford is likewise well known.  Like that 
entrepeneur, Bill wants to move Americans forward a 
quantum jump.  Mentufacturing could be the answer 
for him, as well as the nation."

"Mentufacturing mania will probably pique everyone's
fancy in the next few months," said computer magazine
writer John Dvorak. "It's a great concept, but making 
it concrete may take a little longer."

"I believe everyone from education to industry will 
rush to go 'mental' on the Information Superhighway, 
now that the Vice President has put this welcome 
proposal onto the playing field," said Congressman 
Edward Markey (Dem.), also in attendance at 
the press meeting.

Gore concluded the press conference by paraphrasing 
the Grolier dictionary's definition of 
"mentufacture."  "To mentufacture is to engage 
in the _manufacture_ of the God which resides in 
every man: the fruit of the soul, our minds, ourselves.  
Thank you ladies and gentlemen."




EXPERIMENTATION ON HUMANS: SECRECY AS A MEANS 
FOR AVOIDING STICKY PUBLIC RELATIONS GAFFES 

On February 22, a rather ugly Atomic Energy Commission
document was finally declassified, indicating the Cold War
US government's determination to hide radiation 
experimentation on citizens in order to prevent 
"adverse effect on public opinion or result in 
legal suits."

Written by Colonel O. G. Haywood, Jr. on April 17, 1947,
under the imprimatur of the AEC, to a Dr. Fidler at 
Oak Ridge, Tennessee, the letter states in rock-ribbed 
bureaucratese:

Subject:  MEDICAL EXPERIMENTS ON HUMANS

      1. It is desired that no document be released 
which refers to experiments with humans and might have
adverse effect on public opinion or result in legal
suits.  Documents covering such work field should be
classified "secret".  Further work in this field in the
future has been prohibited by the General Manager.
It is understood that three documents in this field have
been submitted for declassification and are now classified
"restricted".  It is desired that these documents be
reclassified "secret" and that a check be made to insure
that no distribution has inadvertantly been made to
the Department of Commerce, or other off-Project
personnel or agencies.

Steven Aftergood of the Federation of American Scientists
in Washington, D.C., points out in the March 1994 Secrecy 
& Government Bulletin, "The practice of classifying 
information in order to prevent embarrassment to an agency 
has long been prohibited. And yet it is commonplace."

The AEC letter was unearthed by Rep. John Dingell's 
subcommittee on oversight with copies available directly
from the FAS.


VISITING THE NATIONAL ATOMIC MUSEUM:  NO
BOOKWORMS ALLOWED

The National Atomic Museum on dusty Kirtland Air
Force Base in Albuquerque, NM, is a must see for
Cold War historians.  As an example of the 
Orwellian destruction of language and history as
a means of controlling the official record, it is
without peer.

Sitting across the street from Sandia National 
Laboratories and the strangely named International
School for Nuclear Weapons, the national resources 
responsible for what is vulgarly referred to as
the "weaponization" of thermonuclear technology, 
the museum is the place where one can see the mothers
of all bomb-casings.

Curiously, it's also a kind of a-historic black hole
where the post-War tale of high energy physics is
crushed and twisted into an infinitely long bit of
nothing.

The first thing a visitor sees when entering the museum -
a big, beige, cinder block box - is a banner for the
peaceful use of the atom, namely something called
the Godiva project.  Signified by an artist's conception 
of the naked woman on horseback, the Godiva project - as
told by the National Atomic Museum - was a line of 
experiments revolving around the construction of what 
is known to physicists as a "bare critical assembly."  The 
bare critical assembly is merely an apparatus, looking 
much like an interlocking series of coat-hangers, capable 
of sustaining a nuclear chain reaction in air through 
the application of good geometry and the perfectly machined 
pieces of plutonium metal which constitute its fuel source.

At the National Atomic Museum, the _peaceful_ applications 
of this gizmo were - according to the photographic 
record - testing military vehicles and animals for 
their opacity to hard radiation.  This is not easy 
to discern in the exhibit because it's not described on 
museum placards; the visitor must look at the photographs 
closely to see the plastic cages filled with dozens of 
white mice arrayed around the mechanism's fuel elements, 
awaiting their turn at fatal doses of radiation.  During 
a clumsy experiment, one of the Godiva critical assemblies 
generated a shock wave, distorting the fuel elements 
and ruining the mechanism.

Around the corner from the Godiva exhibit come the bombs, or
what's left of them.  Casing upon casing are lined up on
the floor, from a duplicate of the Fat Man - the Nagasaki
bomb - to the monster Mark 17, a 25-foot long, 21-ton hydrogen
bomb, physically the largest critter to ever grace the US
arsenal.

Also on exhibit are some more curious inventions like the
the Davy Crockett, an infantry-launched nuclear projectile.  
The Crockett shell was tested twice during exercises 
called Little Feller and then withdrawn from service over 
the military's concern that a sergeant ought not to have 
control of battlefield nuclear munitions and the presumed 
reluctance of line troops to use a weapon which stood a 
good chance of fragging them in its blast.

Much space in the bomb exhibit at the National Atomic
Museum is devoted to the government's handling, or mishandling,
of what are known as Broken Arrows:  any unexpected event
involving nuclear weapons when not at war, like losing
a bomb.

One of the more spectacular nuclear screw-ups - the loss of
four B-28 H-bombs during an air collision between a B-52
and its refuelling tanker over Palomares, Spain, 
in January 1966 - is portrayed as a public relations 
victory demonstrating the efficiency of the US military.

"You see, Broken Arrow procedures work, none of the bombs
detonated," the museum's exhibit seems to say.  During the
"event," one bomb was recovered from land, one fell into
the Mediterranean but was recovered weeks later, and two 
others scattered plutonium fuel over Palomares when their 
conventional explosives blew up. The US government, along 
with Spanish authorities, scraped up some of the topsoil and
carted it away.

Surprisingly, the National Atomic Museum devotes no space
to the blast effects of nuclear weapons.  Well, what are
they for?

The tourist will also not want to miss the museum's 
description of the efficient and high-tech storage 
of atomic waste generated at places like Hanford, 
Washington, and Rocky Flats, Colorado.  Neatly sealed 
in caves and geologically stable salt deposits; 
trucked across the country in invulnerable concrete 
casks, the museum indicates the citizenry is safe from 
poisonous byproducts of the weapons industry. There's 
no comment on the environmental disasters synonymous 
in the public's mind with the same towns. 

For the more credulous - or the dangerously stupid - the 
museum has a Tonka model-sized waste-carrying truck in 
a plastic showcase.  On the showcase are signs saying 
the model doesn't contain any real nuclear waste.  And 
I thought it did.

Visit the National Atomic Museum in Albuquerque.  You 
can't miss it.  Look for the B-52 in the parking lot.




