REVIEWED: "FUTURE IMPERFECT," HOWARD SEGAL'S
ANSWER TO ALVIN TOFFLER AND THE LIKE-MINDED

In Howard Segal's "Future Imperfect: The Mixed 
Blessings of Technology in America" (University of
Massachusetts Press, $15.95 ppb.), one gets the
history of the American cultural descent into the 
mania of gadget freaks and the schizophrenic 
utopianism and dread of machinery it has spawned.   
And while this sounds like a generic Crypt Newsletter 
wisecrack, it's meant as a compliment, 
because anyone who appears to think the work of 
futurists glorified bullshit deserves all the print 
space he can get.

"Future Imperfect" is a collection of analyses 
and critiques of the image of technology in America 
and how it contrasts with reality.

It's this fascination with an idea - a euphoria
for progress - which has overflowed into daily life 
in the Nineties, loosening almost everyone's 
slippery grip on reality. (For an example, the reader
is invited to review one TV commercial featuring the
balding goofball on lend from the David Letterman 
show whose mission, along with faithful donkey, is 
to be a Paul Revere in service to the cable industry.)

Segal, then, is furnishing the history behind the 
gadget story:  from an excellent piece on Kurt 
Vonnegut's "Player Piano" darkly mirroring US 
fascination with the scientist as national and 
social leader; the creation of an America integrated, 
ordered and spiritually destroyed by supercomputer - 
to the psychology of techno-advertisement for 
the newest computer-chip controlled this, the newest 
hand-held that - which never work as claimed.

In the final chapter of "Future Imperfect" Segal 
sharpens the knife on the beloved coverboys of 
airport newsstand magazines - futurists.

"High tech has spawned a new generation of technological
utopians whose principal allegiance is not to the public
sector, but to the private; whose favored institution is
not big government but the big corporation; and whose
principal motivation is not serious social change but
personal gain -- or prophecy for profits' sake," he
writes.

Of Alvin Toffler, techno-America's high factotum of 
institutionalized bragging:

". . . Toffler's description of the contemporary world,
written in the breathless prose of Time magazine . . .
is rather depressing to contemplate.  Toffler contends
. . . we need new ways of looking at and responding to
the future at hand and, not surprisingly, new visionaries
to guide us to a better world ahead.  Toffler, of course,
is happily available . . ."

Segal's work was written before Alvin and Heidi's current
"War & Anti-War" which, if anything, is even "more depressing
to contemplate" now in its fetish with the imagined 
machinery of a military-industrial future. "Future 
Imperfect" is a book to read in its place, since it not 
only attempts to explain why Americans are hypnotized by 
the image of high-tech, but how they're let down by it, too.


"THE 1994 INTERNET WHITE PAGES":  AT LAST, A PHONEBOOK
FOR THE PATENTLY INSANE

"The 1994 Internet White Pages" by - and this is the first
time I've ever seen what amounts to a phonebook attributed
to two authors - Seth Godin and James S. McBride (IDG Books,
$29.95) is an item on the same plane of significance as 
the Edsel.  Sure everyone made jokes about it, but I bet 
you wish you had one now!  So laugh. As your lips curl
into a sneer over the weirdest thing you'll see in 1994,
know full well the authors will be riding that 
contempt to the bank in wheelbarrows laden with cash 
money.

The "White Pages" is just that: 800+ white pages of 
Internet addresses and the names of those who appear to 
belong to them.  And what will that get you?

It's not clear, but consider:

The "White Pages" has two e-mail addresses for Jean Luc 
Picard, two for Captain Kirk, two for Mr. Spock, 
one for Commander Data, one for Wesley Crusher, one 
for Lestat the Vampire, but none for Peter Parker: the 
Amazing Spider-Man or Alfred E. Neuman.

It has one for "Ludwig Plutonium," an
anonymous Ivy League clown possessed of a kind of
dumb animal cunning, who has seen fit to improve 
on J. S. Bach's  "Breathe On Me, Breath of God" 
with the drily witty lyrics for some song entitled
"CARBON IN ME, CARBON OF PLUTONIUM" which goes like
this:

"Carbon in me, Carbon of Plutonium,
Fill me with life anew
That I may love what thou dost love,
And do what thou superdetermined me to do
Carbon in me, Carbon of Plutonium,
Make my heart pure.
Take me to Thy Protons
to do and to endure.
Breathe in me, Oxygen of Plutonium,
Make me wholly thine.
Take this Earthly part of me.
Nucleosynthesis divine.
Plutonium in me, ATOM Plutonium.
So shall I never die, but live with thee
Part in thy Electron's Biology
Part in thy Proton's Infinity.   ATOM."

[Socko poem not included.]

The book has countless e-mail addresses of college
students, what look to be all the names of
middle-level managers at IBM's HQ in Armonk, NY;
two addresses for "Dark Hacker;" a listing for
"dracula@kraken.micro.umn.edu;" Internet addresses
for most of the Cat family: Bill the Cat, Alley 
Cat, Felix the Cat, Cheshire Cat, Stimpson J. Cat 
and le Chat Blue; and e-mail points for lots of people 
who _appear_ to be quite sane most of the 
time - almost 100,000 of them, in fact.

If you get out your mental pencil and assume that
the Internet currently sports approximately 15
million denizens, the "White Pages" 
lists about 0.66 percent of them. If that
population doubles by October of this year, as some
suggest it could, the book might be expected to
expand to 1600+ pages.  And it has plans to
be updated quarterly.  Heh.

The authors menacingly claim at the end of their
introduction, " . . . you're prohibited by copyright
law from using [the "White Pages"] to create
bulk mailings."  Yes, but the Crypt Newsletter
wouldn't want to have to prosecute that one in copyright
court, buddy. 

The authors also write their list has been purged 
of "obviously-contrived names, and the like."

Indeed, the Crypt Newsletter would be loathe to part
with its copy of Seth Godin and James McBride's "The
1994 INTERNET White Pages."


THE MYSTERIES OF HACKERS or HOW TO PHREAK ON NYNEX WITHOUT
A CLUE:  FALLACIES AND FOIBLES AT THE LOCAL WALDEN'S GENERIC
BOOKMART, PART II

"I've found people even more useful after a book is written.
 They can read the manuscript and may spot the sort of
 howlers that, once in print, will draw you no end of
 angry letters from outraged readers."

                        --Lawrence Block, "Writing
                          the Novel, From Plot to
                          Print"

Last month we reviewed a detective story that attempted to
throw a little color into a bland plot by mixing in a
computer virus.  Fair play compels us to review another
detective series that recently introduced a pair of hackers.

"A Walk Among The Tombstones" was written by Lawrence Block and
is one of a series of books that features Matthew Scudder, an
alcoholic ex-policeman who freelances as a private detective
for New York City's seedier inhabitants.

In this case, Scudder is hired by a drug peddler to find
who kidnapped and dismembered said peddler's wife.  Since
the kidnappers placed several calls _to_ the peddler's
house, Scudder tries to find a listing of the phone numbers
used to place the calls.  Employees of the telephone company
say that there is no way to assemble such a list.  While
Scudder is speaking with a street-wise contact, readers get
their first description of the hackers.

"'So why you be dickin' around with the telephone company
  when you could be comin' to TJ?'

 'You mean you know how to get the numbers from the phone
  company?'

 'No, man.  But I know how to get the Kongs.'

 'The Kongs,' he said.  'Jimmy and David.'

 'They're brothers?'

 'Ain't no family resemblance far as I can see.  Jimmy
  Hong is Chinese and David King is Jewish.  Least his
  father is Jewish.  I think his mother might be Rican.'

 'Why are they the Kongs?'

 'Jimmy Hong and David King?  Hong Kong and King Kong?'

 'Oh.'

 'Plus their favorite game used to be Donkey Kong.'

 'What's that, a video game?'

 'I told you what happens to guys hang around the arcade,
  how you can get so good an' then there ain't no better
  for you to get?  So you lose interest....What some dudes
  get interested in is computers.  What I heard, the Kongs
  was into computers all along, fact they used a computer
  to stay ahead of the video games, know what the machine
  was going to do before it could do it...So they into
  computers, they what you call hackers.'"

The ensuing description sets the stage for Scudder as the
straight man:  He is continually asking the questions only
a techno-virgin could dream up.  It's a role that will be
continued when he actually meets the Kongs.

"'Man, you want something from the phone company, you
  don't call no operator.  Don't mess with no vice
  president, either.  You call the Kongs.  They get into
  the phones and crawl around in there, like the phone
  company's a monster and they swimmin' in its bloodstream.
  You know that picture, whatchacallit, Fantastic Voyage?
  They take a voyage in the phones.'

 'I don't know,' I said.  'If an executive at the
  company can't figure out how to extract that data--'

 'Man, ain't you listenin'?'  He sighed, then sucked hard
  hard on his straw and drained the last of his Pepsi.
  'You want to know what's happenin' on the streets, what's
  goin' down on the Deuce or in the Barrio or in Harlem,
  who do you go and ask?  The fuckin' mayor?'"

During my first read, I was cautiously enthusiastic at
this point.  Sane authors normally don't waste 
time giving colorful background on characters they're 
going to trash later.  Block had also set up a character
that could ask the questions a rookie would need answered
to understand hacking in general.  My one lagging concern
was the mention of using a computer to figure out what
an arcade game would do next.  While theoretically feasible,
it seemed far-fetched.  Not many arcade owners are willing
to let strangers hook a laptop into their thousand dollar
machines.  Other alternatives for what might have been meant
seemed even more forced.  I'll spill the beans and let you
know that it's a pattern to be repeated in later
sections of the book: the careful portrayal of realistic
and likeable characters interlaced with the careless
presentation of spurious technological feats.

On the portrayal of hackers, check out the following:

"'The thing is,' Jimmy Hong said, 'we have to be careful.
  People in suits are convinced that hackers are the
  biggest threat to corporate America since the Yellow Peril.
  The media is always running stories about what hackers
  could do to the system if we wanted to.'

 'Destroying data,' David King said.  'Altering records.
  Wiping out circuitry.'

 'It makes a good story, but they lose sight of the fact
  that we never pull that shit.  They think we're going to
  put dynamite of the railroad tracks when all we're doing
  is hitching a free ride.'

 'Oh, every once in a while some nitwit introduces a virus--'

 'But most of that isn't hackers, it's some jerk with a
  grudge against a company or somebody introducing a
  glitch into the system by using bootleg software.'"

Argh!  There it is again.  Hackers being reasonable and
responsible, but somehow believing that glitches are
introduced into the system by bootleg software.  Somehow
Mr. Badger doubts that an illicit copy of Word Perfect
can bring anything down, much less the telephone system.

I will have to omit much of what follows, mainly because,
as the character Scudder states, "Once they [the hackers]
decided they trusted you, you couldn't get them to shut up."
[Insert loud, prolonged laughter from Mr. Badger at this
point.]  The following will be of interest, however.  The
scene is a hotel room Scudder has rented for the Kongs to
use while hacking into NYNEX.

"The telephone had been relocated from the bedside table
 to the desk, with something called an acoustic coupler
 attached to its earpiece and something else called a
 modem plugged into its rear.  It shared the desk with
 the Kongs' laptop computer.

"Jimmy Hong was seated at the desk, his fingers flashing
 on the computer's keyboard, then punching numbers on the
 phone."

Since there are half a dozen hacking programs capable of
