FORTUNE AND MISFORTUNE, FORBES AND FLUBS, THE STATE OF THE
VOICE AND THE VOICE OF THE STATE; READINGS FROM THE
BUSINESS SECTION OF THE NEWSSTAND

A quick scan of two business magazines, Fortune and Forbes,
shows the industry may be acquiring needed
scepticism and savvy when it comes to technological
issues.  And actually, this is unfair.  Business magazines
have seen so many promising industries waver and crash
they show much more restraint than commonly seen in
strength-through-joy publications like Time and Newsweek.

There are real signs of change in the March 21, 1994
issue of Fortune.  True, it still lists Trip Hawkins (CEO of
3DO) in its list of "America's Smartest Young Entrepreneurs."
But now they start by saying,

        "Depending on whom you ask, Trip Hawkins is either
         a great visionary or a highly skilled hype artist.

Mr. Badger will refrain from jumping on the bandwagon of sceptics
regarding 3DO and its creators.  What is beyond dispute is that
3DO is basing its corporate strategy on a concept so vast and
sweeping that it will be either an enormous success or a total
failure.  Thumbs up to Fortune for letting Trip Hawkins
state it in his own words:

        "We're not going to make any real money until our
         player is in over half the homes in America."

If you question why Mr. Badger heavily criticizes some visionaries
and remains silent about this one, the reason is simple.
Mr. Badger admires people who have a vision _and_ stake a large
part of themselves and their resources in working to create that
vision.  Those that can, do.  Those that can't, become college
professors.  The totally incompetent become journalists.  As
founder of Electronic Arts, a company that designs videogames for
other manufacturers, Hawkins has succeeded once.  While Mr. Badger
wouldn't like the odds Hawkins is facing, he admires the bravado.

Other praise for Fortune magazine comes for their article on the
Baby Bells.  It contains an analysis of each of the seven Bells
with a concise picture of their financial status and strategy for
future development.  Mr. Badger applauds the restraint needed to
ignore the mega-mergers (which aren't working out, anyway) and
focus on the details.  All Mr. Badger can say is:  it's as boring
and tedious as a chess game critique, but he hasn't read it
anywhere else.  If you're willing to dwell on details, check it
out.

It's a disappointment to go from the Baby Bell analysis to
"Reality Boost," a one page article immediately after 
the analysis. The article is about the use of headset 
displays that superimpose information to the users vision. 
Readers will know of military pilots' use of head up 
displays that allow the user not only to view terrain, 
but also superimpose targeting and flying data on a glass 
screen.  Boeing is attempting to develop this same 
technology to help workers "do complex wiring or place 
the perfect rivet."  Can you say "frivolous defense 
conversion project"?

Fortune's assessment:

        "It will be several years before augmented-reality 
         systems appear in factories or offices.  Today's 
         position-tracking devices don't work well around 
         too much metal and noise, and better displays and 
         smaller computers are needed.  Even then, improving 
         on nature will come at a price: . . . Boeing's 
         reality augmenter [is expected]
         to cost more than $10,000 per worker."

Considering that one of the examples of such a 
system being developed "shows how to change the toner 
cartridge and add paper to a laser printer," Crypt 
Newsletter believes that some people,
at least, inhale very, very deeply.

In other trends, the Village Voice continues its unusual
obsession with inconsequential wackos of the digital world.
"My Log-On, Myself:  Jeff Yang On-Line" in the March 8, 1994
issue is a case in point.  Is it ethnography, epistemology, or
ethics?  Essay, expostulation, exculpation or the work of
someone who has read "Gravity's Rainbow" far too many 
times?  Whatever, it has caused Mr. Badger to create a new 
rule of thumb for "technological" articles:  If it even 
hints at a comparison between Plato's cave and a computer 
screen, abort reading and trash.  Another clue: You will 
want to pass on the publication if the cover infrequently 
makes hard news share time with investigative exposes of 
something like, er, African-American drag queens.

Mr. Badger's home town paper, "The State," earns a prize for
an approach diametrically contrary to the Village Voice.
Each Monday it includes a "Moneywise" supplement.  The editors
have taken to reprinting short articles of interest to 
computer users.  The March 14, 1994 issue focused on tax 
related software. One article profiled convenient features 
in accounting software (these ranged from the 
banal "ease of use" to the presence of audit
alarms that indicate when you are becoming too aggressive in
declaring write-offs).  Another listed three tax packages,
stated the costs and benefits of each, along the most frequent
complaints of actual users.  A third article went into 
available sources for help in tax presentation on various 
on-line services.

Most issues also profile local computer users.  The selection
has been varied, interviewing everybody from game players to
entrepreneurs breaking into the graphics business.  The users
have ranged from die-hard technoids to techphobes.  (In fact,
the only constant has been their wish list:  more RAM.  Sounds
painfully familiar, doesn't it?)   

This practical approach is welcome relief from the
New Age misery inflicted on the computer world.  [Mr. Badger
knows, just KNOWS, that we will soon have books like:  Computer
Users That Howl with the Wolves;  Iron Wrists: Overcoming
Carpal Tunnel Syndrome and Uniting the Yin with the Yang.]
The State is part of the Knight-Ridder chain, so this trend
could be passed on at a newsstand near you.

