SCIENTIFIC AMERICAN:  A USERS GUIDE TO WHAT'S READABLE & WHAT'S
NOT


"Like other sciences, economics has two sides:  
the theories and the facts."

                   --Wilfred Beckerman, "In Defence of
                     Economic Growth" 


The March, 1994 Scientific American has two articles 
worth haggling over.

"Wire Pirates" is an introduction to security problems 
on Internet. Editorial opinions at Crypt Newsletter 
were divided. Mr. Badger saw it as a great intro to the 
general concept of security on Internet.  Urnst saw 
it as just another vague story.

Who's right?  Probably both of us.  (Hey, Mr. Badger may kiss
ass, but he has his pride.)  I actually liked the article 
because it _was_ banal and vague.  I have used copies of it
to fend off unwanted inquires from slackers who believe I'm a
digital deity.  (And believe me, if anyone mistakes 
Mr. Badger for a technological guru, we are dealing with 
minds slightly - only slightly, mind you - greater than those 
of the Mackinaw trout.)

Urnst Kouch is correct in that the article contains less 
useful technical data than Computer Emergency Response 
Team action memos, relies only upon SRI-approved 
experts reciting reasonable-sounding boilerplate, and has 
illustrations which serve no purpose other than filling out 
the page count.  Then again, Urnst approaches Ubermensch 
status in his ability to digest arcane software packages 
and, perhaps, was expecting just a little -
more.

So what's the final verdict?  How about a compromise?  Urnst
Kouch says not to pollute your mind with it; Mr. Badger
recommends giving it to other people whose minds are gone 
already.

The second article is "The Analytical Economist," a regular
feature in Scientific American.  It has only a perfunctory
relevance to computer issues, but peevishness, presumption,
and a predatory attitude have carried me far in
life and I see no reason to change now.

In "The Analytical Economist," the authors are examining 
a time-honored tenet of economists:  Large scale production 
is more advantageous than small scale.  In other words, 
no matter what the product, when it's manufactured in 
greater and greater quantities, cost per unit decreases. 

Take cars.  They would be impossibly expensive
if the factories, workers, and tools needed were charged in
the cost of one vehicle.  But when millions of cars are made,
the cost of manufacturing is spread out over each of the cars.
Likewise, the Air Force might expect economics of scale to
reduce the per unit cost of the MILSTAR from $13.7 billion
to maybe, say, only 4 or 5 billion as a few more roll off
the assembly line.

This led some economists - like Karl Marx - to theorize that
large businesses would one day squash small ones.  Small-sized
firms would simply lack the ability to match the reduced cost
per unit of large firms.

Economies of scale do not get much attention, mainly because
it has become painfully apparent that large-size firms can
collapse in spite of the benefits of large-scale production.
Remember Chrysler?  It didn't matter that they were spreading
the fixed costs of manufacturing over millions of units,
consumers wouldn't touch the product.  The same pattern was
repeated on a larger scale in the managed economies of the
Soviet Union.  And take Northrop's B-2 bomber, which appears 
to be getting more expensive as greater numbers are 
manufactured.

One may wonder why how such a simple, narrow rule 
became the basis for monetary management, to the exclusion
of almost all else.  This is because the average 
economist has been cursed by vision more myopic 
than the mole. In fact, one of the basic approaches 
in economics is to exclude all factors except for 
the one being manipulated and the one being 
measured.  This leads economists to 
say, "All other things being equal, X will cause Z."

Unfortunately, this is of only limited value in
complex systems.  A large company may benefit from the 
reduced cost per unit, but also become less adaptive in 
the process.  Understand that the myopic
vision of an economist allows the emphasis of principles 
that would not be apparent otherwise.  Also, in real 
life, if there are 1000 economic principles that apply 
to a given situation, failure to pay attention to 
one of them may invalidate the effort given to the 
other 999.

What in the world does this have to do with computer 
technology?

Modern economists - or at least the writers of "The 
Analytical Economist" - wonder if the use of microchips 
may invert the traditional economy of scale.  Will 
small firms using computers/automation have an advantage 
over large firms using computers/automation?

The question isn't without interest, but at this point 
the article strayed from its descriptive title.  
Analysis _normally_ means the clear separation of an 
inquiry into its component parts. Science _normally_ 
means a methodical approach to evaluating
hypotheses.  But Scientific American's "Analytical Economist"
saw fit to mix questions regarding the effects of product
customization, the relationship between the scale of production
and the size of the organization and the effect of local
infrastructure on the break-even point in purchasing
new technology into a thumb-sucking muddle.

It concluded:

        "The simple cost-curve portrayal of traditional
         economies of scale may gradually fade from
         future texts.  Perhaps the only certainty in
         the big versus small debate is that to capture
         the subtleties of these arguments the textbooks
         themselves are bound to grow in size."

At least the size of textbooks will get larger. Christ. 
If this is any indication, Mr. Badger is now utterly 
convinced the American I.Q. will decrease.

The failure of "The Analytical Economist" to clearly discern
between these separate issues caused major lapses
in the article's reasoning.  Take the following:

        "In burgeoning service industries . . . the
         new technology minimizes 'transaction costs.'
         A computer network, for example, makes it
         possible to enter a piece of information such
         as an airplane reservation just once.  The
         goal is not to pump an ever increasing amount
         of bits through an electronic pipeline but
         rather to make the most use of each bit."

Ridiculous!  The goal of General Motors isn't
to use screws.  Here is the true parallel:  General 
Motors and the travel agent take in money on each
unit of service.  From money received, they deduct the
cost of performing the service (for GM that mean screws,
for the travel agent, it means other fees).  Both can
increase their profit by cutting expenses (reducing 
the number of screws, reducing electronic duplication 
of effort). But the tenet of economies of scale is 
that the overhead on each unit can be further reduced if 
fixed costs are spread over a larger number of units.  
To confuse the two issues is embarrassing.  Yes, 
smaller does mean better, when it comes to the 
costs of materials used.  Yes, larger does mean 
better when it comes to distributing fixed costs.

Come on, Scientific American.  At least pass your
articles by management before you publish.  Not
only will the laugh help relieve some stress, it
will let you know who shouldn't be allowed 
anywhere near the books.
          

"But the age of chivalry is gone.  That of sophists,
 economists, and calculators, has succeeded; and the
 glory of Europe is extinguished forever."

                  --Edmund Burke, "Reflections on
                    the Revolution in France"


