TECHNICAL ADDITIONS: BATCH VIRUS AND THE COMPLETE
DISASSEMBLY OF THE TUNNELING TOOLKIT DEMO

In this issue, I've included an analysis and
quick and dirty disassembly of Stormbringer's
BATCH VIRUS, an interesting program which
replicates through the lowly batch file.
Stormbringer - a member of the hacking group
phalcon/SKISM and winner of Mark Ludwig's 1st
Virus Writing Contest - has always turned out interesting
code. The BATCH VIRUS is no exeception.

A "parasitized" host batch file altered by
BATCH VIRUS is included as the file VIRUS.BAT. Placing 
it in a directory with any batch files and execution
will result in BATCH VIRUS attaching itself to
all uninfected batch files, too.  The curious will
notice most anti-virus programs ignore batch files
during virus checking unless specifically ordered not to.
However, it is hardly necessary to have or look at
anti-virus software to work with BATCH VIRUS.

See BATVIR.ASM for a more detailed explanation of
BATCH VIRUS.

More recently, a hacker named Private Research 
disassembled the complete Kohntark Tunneling Toolkit
included in Crypt Newsletter 18.  The Toolkit was
designed to demonstrate the virus phenomenon of
tunneling, or burrowing beneath the operating
system, to bypass any software specifically
engineered to trap or monitor virus-like activity.
The Toolkit was a plug and play module originally
shoe-horned into the YB family of demonstrator 
viruses.

Private Research notes that the Tunneling Toolkit
uses the same code as another tunneling virus
named Dudley.

While it is difficult to imagine the computer novice
getting himself into serious trouble with the
BATCH VIRUS, it should be mentioned that allowing it
to infect all batch files on a machine would at the
very least, make the machine run "bumpy" until
the virus was removed.  BATCH VIRUS can easily be
removed at any time by opening infected batch files
with any text editor and erasing the lines of the
batch file responsible for BATCH VIRUS.

In addition, the code for BATCH VIRUS could be assumed
to be beyond the comprehension of a user who bought
his first computer mere months ago.  In this case,
the reader should familiarize himself with the basic
operation of batch files, included in a GOOD MS/PC-DOS
reference. (Hint: not the DOS 6 manual - DOS 5 is a little
better and any book by Kris Jamsa or Jeff Prosise devoted
to DOS is perfect.)

Understanding the assembly language code in BATVIR.ASM -
and KRTTDEMO.ASM - will take a great deal more time
as the entire subject cannot be taught while the user 
is standing on one foot.  Reading earlier issues of
the Crypt Newsletter would be helpful in understanding
assembly language in viruses; a familiarity with 
assembly language in any number of systems programming
references for the IBM-compatible PC is even better, but
beyond the scope of the Crypt Newsletter 24.

Remember, even being thought of as one who messes about
with computer viruses can be hazardous to your reputation
and peace-of-mind in our overly bureaucratic society.

